  "analysis_md": "# Per-tensor Shannon-floor analysis on PR106 substrate\n## Why PR103 AC tensors regress vs brotli on PR106 (information-theoretic)\nShannon's source coding theorem states that no lossless code can compress a stationary source below its empirical conditional entropy `H_k` bits/symbol (for any context order k). A symbol-frequency-only entropy coder (PR103's q8 AC) targets `H_0`. A context-aware coder (brotli's LZ77 + Huffman + context model) targets `H_k` for some k >= 1.\nTherefore the gap `bits_per_symbol_ac - bits_per_symbol_brotli > 0` is a *direct empirical lower bound* on `H_0 - H_k` \u2014 the redundancy in conditional structure that brotli is exploiting and AC is blind to.\n### Aggregate measurements (28 tensors, n=228,958 symbols)\n- **Shannon floor (H_0, i.i.d. bound)**: 167,570 bytes\n- **Shannon floor (H_2, order-2 bound)**: 88,983 bytes\n- **Actual brotli output (sum)**: 170,096 bytes (1.0151 \u00d7 H_0; 1.9116 \u00d7 H_2)\n- **Actual AC output (PR103 indices only)**: 161,388 bytes\n- AC does not regress on any tensor on this substrate.\n\n### No AC regressions on this substrate. Top 3 AC-favorable tensors\n| idx | name | gap (bytes) | H_0 (bits) | H_2 (bits) | n_symbols |\n|---:|:-----|------------:|-----------:|-----------:|----------:|\n| 0 | `stem.weight` | -260 | 5.2221 | 4.0054 | 48,384 |\n| 6 | `blocks.2.weight` | -247 | 6.3183 | 2.6737 | 34,992 |\n| 4 | `blocks.1.weight` | -241 | 5.9173 | 3.4619 | 46,656 |\n\n### Implication for the \u03b4\u03b5\u03b6 training objective\nIf we train weights so the conditional distribution `p(X_t | X_{t-1}, ...)` becomes uniform \u2014 i.e. `H_2 -> H_0` \u2014 then brotli loses its context advantage and AC catches up. Per-tensor entropy targets for the \u03b4\u03b5\u03b6 objective:\n\n    L_entropy = sum_idx ( H_0(idx) - H_2(idx) ) * lambda_idx\n\nminimizing this drives every tensor's `H_2` toward its `H_0`, removing the PR103 regression by construction. The per-tensor (H_0 - H_2) numbers in the JSON output give the gradient targets directly.\n\n### Operational corollary (Op2 auto-fallback)\nOn any substrate where `bits_per_symbol_ac > bits_per_symbol_brotli` for a tensor, the canonical Op2 wrapper SHOULD fall back to brotli for that tensor. The per-tensor table in this JSON provides the exact decision matrix.\n"
